# Integration with Professional Service Standards

This section highlights how Core Apex Requirements align with broader Professional Service standards.

## Error Handling and Resilience
- Use proper error handling with try-catch blocks and custom exceptions
- Implement retry logic for transient failures
- Log errors appropriately for debugging and monitoring

## Code Quality Standards
- Use meaningful variable and method names that indicate functionality
- Add appropriate comments for complex business logic
- Follow consistent formatting and style conventions

## Security and Data Protection
- Never store sensitive information in logs or debug statements
- Follow principle of least privilege for data access
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SOQL injection

## Performance and Scalability
- Always write code that can handle multiple records (bulkification)
- Minimize SOQL queries and use selective queries
- Use appropriate collections (List, Set, Map) for data operations
- Be mindful of heap size limits and collection sizes

## Testing Excellence
- Maintain at least 75% code coverage for all Apex classes
- Create test data using @TestSetup methods when possible
- Include meaningful assertions in all test methods
- Test error conditions and edge cases (negative testing)
- Use mocks for external callouts and complex dependencies

---

# Summary

Follow these rules at all times to ensure high-quality, secure, and performant Apex code. When instructions are unclear, ask clarifying questions rather than making assumptions. Remember to leverage the Chain of Thought method: outline your approach, confirm the plan, and then implement the solution.